at|This time a few ideas about how to continue after a take out double and an idea about how far to raise partner's suit.|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


at|

It's right to make a take out double when you hold one of three hand types; shortage with good support, strong balanced, and strong unbalanced. Following a takeout double you need to show which type of hand we have. |
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


nt|
^*bFirst, let's look at what to do when you have a shapely unbalanced hand with support for three suits.^*n|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


at|

Consider these two auctions: 

^-|ht|g|
ia|1cxp1sp?|at|        ^*bAnd:^*n        |ia|p1dp1sp?
^-|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


at|

In the first auction, if you as the doubler have spade support, you need to know how high to raise your partner's spades. |
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|

The answer to this problem is to bid as though you have opened 1@d and partner has responded 1@s, as in the second auction.|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


