pg| ***** 12 ***** |


nt|
^*bHand 32^*n @2is a very sound take out double. If partner had bid 1@s over 1@d, then a raise to 3@s would be about right. Just bid the same way. Bid 3@S.
@4|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


nt||pn|Hand 33|
md|4hsakj9haqj6dkjt3c3|
mb|1cxp1sp?|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


at|

^*bHand 33^*n is a very fine hand. Show this by bidding 4@s.|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


nt|
In summary, when you have support, raise partner's suit as though you had opened 1 of a minor. |
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


at|

Should partner bid no trumps, then you can raise him as you know how strong his hand is. Bid game or invite depending on your combined values. |
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


bt||nt|
^*bHow do you show a hand too good to overcall in a suit or one no trump?^*n|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


at|

This is very simple. 

Double and then a new suit shows about eight playing tricks. |
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


at|

Double and then rebidding no trumps at the lowest level shows 18-20 points. |
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|

Double and then jumping shows more. |
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


nt|^-
|ia|1cxp1sp?|at|
^-Rebids:|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


at|

1NT - Shows a balanced hand with 18-20 points.|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


at|

2NT - Shows a balanced hand with 21-23 points.|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


at|

2@c - Game forcing. This cue bid shows a very strong hand.|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


at|

2@d/ 2@H - This shows a minimum of 8 playing tricks in diamonds/hearts. Forcing for one round.|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


at|

3@d/ 3@h - These are rather uncommon and should show a hand with about 10 playing tricks and good shape. Game forcing.|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


at|

That's really all there is to it.|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


